  "prompt": "Is there a way to for my Google Calendar to manage my Office 365 Exchange Cal that doesn't involve using the Subscribe Option?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several ways to manage your Office 365 Exchange Calendar in Google Calendar without using the subscription option. Here are a few methods you can consider:\n\n1. **Use a Third-Party Integration Tool:**\n   - Tools like Zapier or Integromat allow you to set up workflows to sync events between Google Calendar and Office 365. You can create triggers to add events in one calendar when events are created or modified in the other.\n\n2. **Import and Export Events:**\n   - You can export events from your Office 365 calendar and import them into Google Calendar:\n     - In Office 365, go to your calendar, and look for the option to export (usually in the settings or menu).\n     - Save the exported calendar file (usually in .ics format) and then go to Google Calendar, where you can import the file.\n   - Note that this method doesn't create a dynamic link, so you'll need to repeat the process to update events.\n\n3. **Use Microsoft Power Automate:**\n   - If you have access to Microsoft Power Automate (formerly Microsoft Flow), you can create a flow that automatically sends new events from Office 365 to Google Calendar. This method provides more customizable options for syncing events.\n\n4. **Manual Entry:**\n   - If you don\u2019t have too many events or don't require real-time updates, you can always enter events manually in both calendars.\n\n5. **Use Google Workspace Sync for Microsoft Outlook:**\n   - If you're using Outlook, you can also use Google Workspace Sync for Microsoft Outlook (if you're a Google Workspace user) to sync your Google Calendar with Outlook, which in turn syncs with your Office 365 Calendar.\n\nEach of these methods has its pros and cons depending on the level of automation or synchronization you require. Choose the one that best fits your needs.",
